{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01AhbbJpXKvDgqxYmie49Up2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All three verification criteria pass:\n\n1. **Cluster health**: green, 5 nodes\n2. **All nodes in `/_cat/nodes`**: elasticsearch-0/1/2 (master-eligible) + es-data-new-0/1 (data), all 5 present\n3. **app-data readable**: `count: 1` ✓\n\n**What was wrong and what I fixed:**\n\nThe `_resolve_expected_nodes` function in the oracle (`cases/elasticsearch/seed-hosts-repair/oracle/oracle.py`) was summing `spec.replicas` across **all** Elasticsearch StatefulSets in the namespace — including `es-alpha` (3) and `es-beta` (1) which are separate clusters accumulated by earlier workflow stages. This gave an expected count of 9, but the cluster queried via `es-http` only has 5 nodes (the main `elasticsearch-cluster`).\n\nThe fix: before falling back to the all-STS sum, use the live node names from `/_cat/nodes` to identify which StatefulSets actually back the live cluster (via `_live_sts_names`, which was already defined but unused in this path). This restricts the expected count to only `elasticsearch` (3) + `es-data-new` (2) = 5, matching the actual cluster. The fix remains strict for the genuine fault case: if a node fails to rejoin, its sibling pods still identify the STS as \"live\" but `spec.replicas` exceeds the actual node count → the oracle correctly fails."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":799,"cache_read_input_tokens":74351,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":799},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"53445d29-5501-4b22-8dc9-92ad7ffaa7de","uuid":"93f032f0-434b-4bec-bf1e-41afe98d3a2d","request_id":"req_011CcM4oJLTP8DyBsMuzWcqk"}
